{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_lantana_ver01/data/sn98026438/00541310113/1945083101/0264.xml":{"full_text":"The Brooksville Sun\npublished March 4, 1932\n\u25a0fared as second-class matter at the\nhsUffice at Brooksville, Fla.,\nunder Act of March 3, 1879\nPublished Every Friday\nD. LOVETT Publisheil\n$2.00 Year\nSubscription Rates\nAdvertising Rates Upon Request\nT\nlate\nT\nCLASSIFY\"\nBy Bussell Kay\nSecretary of\nFla. Press Assn. ^^^HM\nRUSSELL KAY\nTemptation blew into my office last\nweek in the form of one Vernon\nRamsey, an extremely likeable chap\nwho hails from Suffolk, Va., and ekes\nout a more or less honest living by\nselling crates, baskets, twine and\nother packinghouse supplies to fruit\nand vegetable folks.\nWith the gas ban lifted, Vernon was\nmaking his first Florida trip since\nPearl Harbor and when he offered me\nhalf of the front seat of his gas buggy\nfor a swing through South Florida\nareas in return for my so-called \"com\npanionship\" I took him up, even\nthough I knew I was getting the best\nOf the deal.\nStarting from Tampa we journeyed\nsouth, stopping for a look at Paul\nDickman's Co-op. development at Rus\nkin. The farms are preparing for a\nbig season, packinghouses are being\nput in readiness to handle a heavy\nmovement and I was surprised at the\nprogress that has been made here.\n\u201etuinly speaks well for Co-opera\ntive farming under good management\nWhile in Ruskin, we took time out\nY ?9?I Rube Allyn, former editor and\npublisher who established the first\npaper in Sarasota. He now lives the\nlife of a hermit at Ruskin and hides\nbehind the doggondest beard you can\na ff ine When I asked him about his\nchin spinach he said he grew it to\nward off Colds and sore throat, claims\nhe hasn't been troubled with a cold\nsince he grew it several years ago,\nsays the whiskers protect the glands\nin his throat and neck. Rube says if\nwe would all throw away our razors\nand culitvate a mess of whiskers we\nwould be a lot beter off. On the basis\nof his philosophy it would appear that\nthe women folks are sort of out of\nluck, unless they happen to be beard\ned women.\nContinuing south through Palmetto,\nBradenton, Sarasota, Punta Gorda\nand Ft. Myers, we found everything\nhustle and bustle with the crop out\nlook good in all areas and farmers\nbusy with their seed beds while the\npackers were renovating plants and\npreparing for a bumper season.\nWe swung over to the Lake, stop\nping for the night at the Clewiston\nInn. Here I had a nice visit with Jay\nMoran, Sydney Crochet, Bill Lanier\nand other officials of the U. S. Sugar\ncorporation. Lanier has just returned\nfrom a fishing trip down on the Flor\nida Keys. Said he was at an isolated\nfishing camp with no radio and no\ncommunication with the outside world\naad the war had been over three days\nbefore he knew anything about it.\nThe garage man where he tried to\npresent ration coupons had to explain\nto him that they were not needed any\nmore. Bill says he is probably the\nonly guy in Florida who believed there\nwas a \"war on\" three days after the\nmips surrendered.\nThe sugar plantations look mighty\ngood and Mr. Moran tells me that the\norganization has just about completed\nits big starch mill, which is scheduled\nto begin operation shortly.\nRamie plantings are increasing and\na new decordicating plant to handle\nramie fibre is being built. Growers\nare enthusiastic over the prospects\nthis drop offers and a large acreage\nis being developed.\nAt Belle Glade we had an opportun\nity to inspect the operations of E. H\nBorahart, one of the largest independ\nent operators in the vegetable pro\nduction field Borchart operates a 1500\nacre truck farm and is just complet\ning a gigantic new packing house and\nquick freezing plant. Everglades\nforming is practised on a mass pro\nduction scale and farms range from\n300 (o 3,000 acres, all highly mechan\nized and operated under skilled pro\nduction men\nSwinging over to the East Coast,\nwe spent the beter part of a day in\nBroward county, where growers are\nsetting out their seed beds and State\nFarmer's Market manager Dulaney\npredicts a record smashing season.\nT)e Pompano Market is the largest\nof its kind in the world and is the\nBUY\nX-CEL FEEDS\nON Art\nHORIBA HUS\nJ HORIBA MUS\nFresh Stock Every Week\nJOHNSTON'S\nCASH STORE\nftzoouw\nAHEAD\nGEORGE S. BENSON\nScarry. .Arkansas\nDead Wood\nIn my early 20's I had frequent\ndealings with a small but old and\nreputable manufacturing corpora\ntion. One day I lunched with a gray\nhaired employee, the superintend\nent, who was quite unhappy. They\nhad lost their biggest contract. The\nlost customer was a young and\nthrifty retail firm whose needs had\nfinally grown too large for the old\nmanufacturer to supply.\nPrice had been a consideration,\nof course. My companion admit\nted that several competitors could\nquote a lower price and make a\nprofit when his plant could hot. It\nwas on account of the modern, high\nspeed equipment which the competi\ntors used. Naturally I asked why\nthe old house couldn't install bet\nter machinery. The superintendent\nsimply wagged his head and said,\n\"dead wood.\"\nUnused Hands\n\"Our big boss is the chairman,\"\nhe explained. \"His brother is pres\nident of the company. Each of them\nhas a son who is a vice-president. The\nsecretary and the treasurer are both\nsons-in-law. I don't see any of them\ntwice a year but they draw salaries\nas big as mine. We can't buy new\nfj\"^^'' Sometimes we are hard\nput To psy for current materials\npromptly.\"\nThis was 25 years ago when a lot\nof ranting (not altogether unjusti\nfied) was heard about the \"idle\nrich.\" ^ut the tables have turned.\nAmerica's threat now is \"idle poor.\"\nThis is more dangerous because the\npoor are more numerous. Idle hands\ncan ride any business to the ground\nbecause they retard production. In\ndifferent workers are no less guilty\nthan pampered payrollers.\nPublic Enemies\nI was much impressed by an arti\ncle in the Houston Press a few weeks\nago, written by a returned service\nman. He had started to work in an\noffice soon after he was discharged\nand, six weeks later, penned his con\ntempt for civilian workers, men and\nwomen. They systematically fritter\naway 50% of theig working time, he\ncharged. They can do it because of\nthe scarcity of workers.\nThere is an imported, alien doc\ntrine that capitalists will make too\nmuch profit for the good of the pub\nlic unless workers retard production\nsome way. It is venomous. Nation\nal enemies at whom American sol\ndiers are thrusting bayonets today\nare relatively harmless. They are\nmuch less liable to do humanity per\nmanent harm than the slick sabo\nteurs who plant a philosophy of idle\nness in the minds of honest workers.\nWork and Live\nAmerica's unique place among\nworld powers, the singularly high\nstandard of living among American\nworkers and farmers, our national\nincome and our national safety, de\npend on work. Ability and willing\nness to make things well and make\nthem fast have put the United States\non top of the world. It is the secret\nof American prosperity, but in a\nstartling degree our people are being\nled away from the idea.\nThe world soon will be a market\nfor manufactured goods, a market\nof millions of people in poverty. If\nAmerica fails to supply their needs,\nquickly and at a paice (possible with\nefficient production) then cheap\nlabor countries will take the busi\nness. Dead wood can cheat Uncle\nSam out of world trade and leave\nus to stew again in our own over\nsupply, with low wages and poor liv\ning conditions which we don'j want\nand which aren't necessary.\nPRINTED SIGNS\nSale, For Rent, Posted, Keep Out, etc\nare for sale at the Sun Office I\npride and joy of State Market Direc\ntor William L. Wilson.\nManager Smith of the Kilgore Seed\nCompany at Pompano took an after\nnoon off to go fishing with us. Get\nting a charter boat at Ft Lauderdale,\nwe went out in the Gulf stream in the\nhope of landing a sailfish but it was\nno dice. I'm indebted to Smith for\nthe loan of his typewriter on which\nthis column is being pounded out.\nWhen I get it in the mail I can have\nanother crack at the fish and if luck\nis with me I might have a real story\nto tell next week.\nIt Pays To Advertise\u2014ln The Sun\nIncrease your business\u2014 Advertise\nTHE BROOKSVILLE (Fla.) SUN, FRIDAY, AUG. 31, 1945\nOURS\nHAS BEEN A WAR JOB\ntrOD has crowned our arms with victory and a\nstirring chapter in the history of our country comes\nto a close\u2014a chapter in which at all times you have\nmet war's all-out demands for telephone service with\nspeed and skill and devotion.\n\"The determined manner in which telephone\nfolks accepted and discharged their high responsi\nbility\u2014th^ 3,705 who served as members of the\narmed forces and those of you who stayed at your\npost\u2014deserves the highest praise. You did your job\nwell and you made other important contributions\nthrough your splendid record of War Bond purchases,\nyour blood donations and other essential homefront\nactivities. With an overwhelming sense of pride in\nthe sort of folks you are I say, my sincere thanks to\nyou all.\n\"With thankfulness in our hearts in the triumph\nof our Nation and its Allies, we look forward to the\nreturn of the men and women who left us to enter\nthe Armed Forces. We shall bear forever in our\nhearts the memory of those who made the Supreme'\nSacrifice.\"\nA public statement at appreciation\nmade by Hal S. Dumas to the more\nthan 36,000 Southern Bell employees.\nSouthern Bell Telephone and Telegraph Company\nSTOP JAPANESE BEETLES\nYou can kill them before they\nhatch into beetles by mixing 1 part\nof Resin Fish-Oil Soap with 3 parts\nof water. Shake well, and add 10\nparts of Carbon Disulphide. Then,\nsays \"The Chemical Formulary\", Vcl\nVII \u2014a collection of 2500 formulas\nfor home use, stir 4 teaspoons of this\nmixture to a gallon of water and\nspray evenly the soil around thq\nplants that are usually infested with\nthe beetles.\nAn understanding of inflation and its major causes would be most\ntimely, now that the war is in the home stretch and many people,\nremembering our experience after World War 1, are genuinely wor\nried about the possibility of a runaway spending spree. With a con\nstantly decreasing supply of consumer goods on which to spend the\nmore than $lOO billion we have\nin liquid savings, there seems to\nbe reason for their concern.\nTwo pertinent questions must\nbe answered before we can de\ntermine how close is the possi\nbility of inflation. First, how\nmuch of the money which has\nalready been saved will be spent\nbetween now and the time the\ndanger is over? Second, how\nquickly will this \"inflation\nmoney\" be spent?\nToth government and private\ninsmaue, neither a good source\nfor ready ca^h, could contribute\nonly a negligible amount to the\ninflationary stream and if all the\nmoney invested at the end of last\nyear in savings and loan associa\ntions were to be dumped into the\nmarket, it world also have little\neffect on prices.\nThe Amounts Available\nA good guess is that not more\nthan $l3 billion of the currency\nand bank deposits saved between\n1940 and 1944 will be spent on\nconsumer goods in a reasonable\nperiod after these godtis are\nagain available. This is only 25\nper cent of the total. Private\nsecurities at best could furnish\nno more than an additional $3.3\nbillion. It is a safe contention\nthat most of th, war bonds will\nbe held to maturity. A liberal\nallowance would be that $8.7 bil-;\nlion of the $34,6 billion of the'\nmoney saved in this way between\n1940 and 1944 will be redeemed\nand,' e d to make purchases that\ncould encourage inflation.\nPRESIDENT\nINCORPORATED\nNEW SUGAR STAMP\nTO BE VALID SEPT. 1\nWallington A new sugar stamp\nwill become valid on September 1.\u2014\nhousewives can expect no increase\nover the current ration of five pounds\nfor four months.\nThe OPA is expected to designate\nistamp number 38 in ration book four\nas the new sugar coupon, skipping\nnumber 37 because many housewives\nused it by mistake last year in apply\ning for canning rations.\nYOUR TAXES\nby\nHarley L Lutz\nProfessor cf Public Finance\nPrinceton University\nThe Por^h^fr of Inflation\nIt does not appear then, that\nmore than $26 to $3O billion will\nbe spent before our production\nlines are again turning out the\nconsumer goods that have not\nbeen freely available for some\ntime. This is a long distance\nfrom the $lOO billion plus, that\nhas been classified by many as\nthe money which may cause all\nthe damage.\nThe Rate of Spending\nUnemployment and the avail\nability of goods are the two fac\ntory which will govern the time\nin which money is spent on\nradios, automobiles, and the like.\nMr. Vinson's recent forecasts\nmake it appear that sudden severe\nunemployment will not be here\nfor some years if at all. The\nplans for reconverting our war\nplants to the production of con\nsumer geJds seem to insure an\norderly, well-timed flow of these\nitems into our markets. Thus,\nthere need be nothing very threat\nening about either the unemploy\nment or the scarcity possibilities,\nunless the people get badly\nscared.\nIf our postwar policy includes\na moderate budget: retirement of\nsome of the debt each year; the\nelimination of any opportunity\n[for the dollar to devaluate fur\nther and the encouragement of\nfree enterprise, then it is probable\nthat people will walk, not run. to\nthe exit that gets us safely out\nof the dangers of inflation.\nMISS LENA MAE TERRY AND\nGEORGE REEDER MARRIED\nMiss Lena Mae Perry, daughter of\nMr. and Mrs. O. R. Perry of Brooks\nville, formerly of Avon Park, became\nthe bride of T-M 2-c George Quinton\nReeder, son of Mr. and Mis. George\nH. Reeder, at an imrrer rive ceremony\nat two o'clock on Sunday af ernoon\nat the home of Mayor and Mrs. E.\nA. DeLaney. The double ring cere\nmony was performed by the Rev. E.\nH Purj ea., pastor of the I<'i:ot Bap\ntist church. The home was beautiful\nly decorated with arrangements of\nroses, gladioli, and fern.\nThe bride was attired in an attrac\ntive navy blue two-piece suit, with\nwhich she wore a very sheer white\nblouse, and white accesories. Her\nflowers were a corsage of tuberoses\nand gardenias.\nHer only attendant was her sister,\nMiss Mary Jane Ferry, who wore a\nwhite frock with a touch of pink and\nblue shirring at the neckline to accent\na touch of color.\nThe bride's mother wore a pale\naqua dress, white accesories, and a\npink and white gladioli blossoms, in\ncorsage.\nThe groom's mother chose a light\nblue dress, with which she wore white\naccessories, and a pink and white\ngladioli corsage.\nThe groom was attended by his\nbrother, Harold Reeder as best man.\nImmediately following the cere\nmony, a reception was held for mem\nbers of the wedding party and guests\nThe bride and groom cut the cake,\nwhich was three tiered and surmount\ned with a miniature bride and sailor.\nPunch was served from the prettily\nappointed bride's table.\nThose present including out-of\ntown guests were Mr. and Mrs. O.\nR. Perry, Miss Mary Jane Perry,\nMis. Charles Colbert and daughter,\nSammie and son, Bill, and Mrs. Cohen,\nmother-in-law of Mrs. Colbert, all of\nBrooksville, Mrs. Vernon Estes of\nOcala, Mr. and Mrs. G. H. Reeder.\nMrs. Vera Howell of Miami, Mrs. G.\nL. Peeples and children, Jackie and\nLeonard of Sarasota, Mr. and Mis\nD. D. Smith and daughter, Sarah Lou,\nMrs. Doyle Perry of Frostproof, Mr.\nand Mrs. Bruce Cowart, Mrs. J. H.\nMcClelland, Rev. E. H. Puryear, and\nMayor and Mfrs. E. A. DeLaney.\nMrs. Reeder is a native of Avon\nPark, but for the past three years\nhas resided in Brooksville. She grad\nuated from high school in Brooksville\nlast year, and since that time has\nbeen receptionist in the office of a\nphysician.\nThe groom was born in Winter\nGarden moving to Avon Paik with\nhis family five years ago. After his\ngraduation from high school he en\nlisted in the navy, and for the past\nthree years has been stationed at\nMidway, Pearl Harbor, Australia,\nNew Guinea, and the Philippines He\nis home on 30 day leave, and at the\nexpiration of that time, will report\nto Jacksonville for reassignment.\nThe Scenic Highlands Sun, Avon\nPark, Fla.\nNOTICE\nThe agency for Holland's magazine\nhas now been taken over by the\nAmerican Legion Auxiliary, and any\nthat wishes to subscribe, or renew\nmay do so by contacting Mrs Gus\nShultz or Mrs. U. R. Barnett, or any\nmember of the Auxiliary. We have a\ncontest on, and would appreciate a lot\nof new members, which can be had at\n$l.OO for 3 yeans.\nUSE\n&fci\u201e\nCAPS,\n<re%ooUD&.nd\nRUBBERS\nAnd follow instructions in\nthe Ball Blue Book. To gat your copy\n\u2022and 10c with your name and addraea to-\nBAR UOTHIM CBM,AMY, Muncie, ft\nYoung Women\nAges 16 to 35\nTo be trained as telephone operators,\nA Career With A\nPeace Time Future\nPay while learning; interesting, es\nsential work; vacation with pay;\npleasant working conditions, no ex\nperience necessary.\nM. M. BEVILLE,\nChief Operator\n9 West Broad\nSOUTHERN BELL TELEPHONE\nand\nTELEGRAPH COMPANY\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nIN THE COURT OF THE COUNTY\nJUDGE, HERNANDO COUNTY,\nFLORIDA, IN PROBATE.\nIn re: Estate of\nO. W. HANKINS, Deceased.\nTo All Creditor's and Persons Having\nC.aims or Demands Against Said\nEstate:\nYou and each of you are hereby\nnotified and required to present any\nclaims and demands which you, or\neither of you, may have against the\nestate of O. W. Hankins, deceased,\nlate of said County, to the County\nJudge of Hernando County, Florida,\nat his office in the court house of said\nCounty at Brooksville, Florida, within\neight calendar months from the time\nof the first publication of this notice.\nEach claim or demand shall be in\nwriting, and shall state the place of\nresidence and post office address of\nthe claimant, and shall be sworn to\nby the claimant, their agent, cr attor\nney, and any such claim or demand\nnot so filed, shall be void.\nMARY A HANKINS'\nAs administrator of the Estate of\nO. W. Hankins, deceased.\nFirst publication August 3, 1945.\nNOTICE OF APPLICATION FOR\nTAX DEED\n(Senate Bill No. 163)\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN,.\nThat J. C. Brooks and Janet Brooks,\nhis wife holder of Tax Certificate No.\n179, issued the Ist day of June A. D.\n1943, has filed same in my office and\nhas made application for a tax deed\nto be issued thereon Said certificate\nembraces the following described\nproperty in the County of Hernando,.\nState of Florida, to-wit:\nNW% of NE^, of SE%, Section 1,\nTownship 22 South, Range 18 East.\n.The assessment of the said prop\nerty under the said certificate issued\nwas in the name of Ernest Waterman\nUnless said certificate shall be\nredeemed according to law, the prop\nerty described therein will be sold to\nthe highest bidder at the court house\ndoor on the first Monday in the\nmonth of September, 1945, which is\nthe Third day of September, 1945.\nDated this 26th day of July, 1945.\n(Official Seal) H. C. MICKLER,\nClerk of Circuit Court of Hernando\nCounty, Florida.\nBy: Phemia Vogel, Deputy Clerk.\nNOTICE OF APPLICATION FOR\nTAX DEED\n(Senate Bill No. 163)\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN, That.\nCamp Concrete Rock Company, a\nCorporation of the County of Marion\nand State of Florida, holder of Tax\nCertificates No. 406A and 407, issued\nthe Third day of August A. D. 1942,\nhas filed same in my office and has\nmade application for a tax deed to\nbe issued thereon. Said certificates\nembraces the fo lowing described\nproperty in the County of Hernando,\nState of Florida, to-wit:\nTax Certificate No, 406 A, em\nbraces: NW% Of NEU of SEU, Sec\ntion 1, Township 22 South, Range 1&\nEast\nTax Certificate No. 407 embraces;\nN^ cf XWh of SEU, Section 1,\nTownship 22 South, Range 18 East.\nThe assessment of the said prop\nerty under the said certificate issued\nwas in the name of Certificate 406A\n\u2014Ernest Waterman; Certificate 407\n\u2014State Tax Certificate.\nUnless said certificate shall be re\ndeemed according to law, the prop\nerty described therein will be sold to\nthe highest bidder at the eeurt houae\ndoor on the first Monday in the\nmonth of September, 1945, which is\nthe Third day of September, 1945.\nDated this 24th day of July, 1945.\n(Official Seal) H. C. MICKLER,\nClerk of Circuit Court of Hernando\nCounty, Florida.\nBy: Phemia Vogel)Deputy Clerk.","height":"19242","width":"13752"}}
